A further thought about specifics to check:

In a browser, it&#39;s *possible* that the site runs the 
resolution-detecting Javascript once, then either (a) sets a cookie 
affecting future behavior, and visits another URL; or (b) redirects to a 
resolution-specific URL/subsite.

In those cases, you could analyze what&#39;s happening, likely through using 
the &quot;Developer Tools&quot;/Firebug console of the browser to observe the 
exact requests and code run by the browser. Then, make Heritrix simulate 
the same effect, by manually setting the same cookie, or adding the 
resolution-specific entry URL as an extra seed. That *might* be enough 
for further outlink URL-visits to also receive good content.

On the other hand, if the resolution-detecting Javascript controls page 
display via repeated &quot;AJAX&quot; loads, or checks again on each followup 
page, the site may be hard or impossible to collect without true 
in-crawler Javascript execution (which Heritrix does not do).

- Gordon

